<li>In Example 5.3.1, note that we are trying to find a solution y
to (5.7)
satisfying the zero boundary conditions (5.8).  Then it was confusing
as the problem needed to solve for \(y_c\) was simply using \(y,\)
but right after that, we write y for the solution of the entire
problem.  So use \(w\) for the problem used to solve for \(y_c\) so that
\(y\) is only used for the entire problem.  In the setup for \(w\)
we now mark the \(f(x) \) and \(g(x) .\)  Then when we write
out the solution we mention again that it is a solution to (5.7)
subject to (5.8).
<li>In the discussion after Remark 6.4.2, improve the exposition about
differentiating under the integral: Emphasize we are
assuming that the functions are zero for negative \(t\)
and add more detail to the footnote.
<li>In section 7.2, use expressions like \(4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2\)
instead of \((4)(3)(2)\) as it is less busy, more readable, and
slightly shorter, especially when a longer list is involved.
<li>In Example 7.2.2, reword the part where the general
terms for the coefficients are obtained to be more logical,
